ale":"1417–Overleden","1435–Male":"1435–Overleden","1437–Male":"1437–Overleden","1438–Female":"1438–Overleden","1440–Male":"1440–Overleden","1445–Male":"1445–Overleden","1402–Female":"1402–Overleden","1437":"1437","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","about 1435":"circa 1435","1440":"1440","ABT 1437":"circa 1437","about 1440":"circa 1440","Abt 1438":"1438","1417":"1417","1438":"1438","Waye by Ashburton, Devon, England":"Waye by Ashburton, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Barnshill, Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1402–":"1402–Deceased","1417–Male":"1417–Deceased","1435–Male":"1435–Deceased","1437–Male":"1437–Deceased","1438–Female":"1438–Deceased","1440–Male":"1440–Deceased","1445–Male":"1445–Deceased","1402–Female":"1402–Deceased","1437":"1437","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","about 1435":"about 1435","1440":"1440","ABT 1437":"about 1437","about 1440":"about 1440","Abt 1438":"1438","1417":"1417","1438":"1438","Waye by Ashburton, Devon, England":"Waye by Ashburton, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Barnshill, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French, English, Dutch, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and Croatian; Breton (also <b>Le Baron</b>): from Old French <i>barun</i>, <i>baron</i>, Middle English <i>barun</i>, <i>baroun</i>, Middle Dutch <i>baroen</i>, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and dialectal Croatian <i>baron</i> ‘baron’ (i.e. a nobleman ranking below an earl and above a knight), a title of nobility which was in England also awarded to certain freemen of the cities of London and York and of the Cinque Ports. As a surname it is unlikely to be a status name denoting a person of rank. Generally, it referred to service in a baronial household or was acquired as a nickname by a peasant who had ideas above his station or applied to a man showing characteristics of a nobleman. See also 3 and 4 below, compare   Barron   and   Lebaron  .","French: habitational name from (Le) Baron, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Lebaron  .","German: status name for a freeman or baron, from <i>barūn</i> ‘imperial or church official’, a loanword in Middle High German from Old French (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Barron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Francisco, Carlos, Miguel, Raul, Pedro, Ruben, Alfredo, Luis.","Scottish: status name from Scots <i>baron</i>, which in the Highlands denoted a small proprietary landholder. In Angus it alluded specifically to a tenant of one of the small baronies attached to the Abbey of Coupar Angus. The surname was taken by Scottish migrants to Ulster. Compare   Baron  .","Scottish: shortened form of <b>McBarron</b>, from Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bharain</b> ‘son of the baron’. See   Baron   and 1 above."]},{"name":"Boron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Krystyna, Edyta, Leszek, Mieczyslaw, Mieczyslawa, Wladyslaw.","Polish (<b>Boroń</b>): from a pet form of the personal names <i>Borzysław</i> or <i>Borzymir</i>, formed with the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’ (from Old Slavic <i>boriti se</i>).","French: habitational name from a place so called in Franche-Comté."]},{"name":"Baro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Manuel, Ana, Angel, Carlos, Cesar, Fernando, Jesus, Jose, Orlando, Ramon, Rosalia.  Italian Guido, Angelo, Carmelo, Federico, Lucio.","Catalan (<b>Baró</b>): status name from <i>baró</i> ‘free man, baron’ (see   Baron   1), or a habitational name from a place so named.","Hungarian (<b>Báró</b>): status name from <i>báró</i> ‘baron’. In the form <b>Baró</b>, it could be from a pet form of the personal names <i>Barabás</i> (see   Barabas  ) or <i>Bertalan</i>."]},{"name":"Barona","meanings":["Spanish: from the feminine form of <b>Barón</b> ‘baron’ (see   Baron  ), applied as a nickname or as an occupational name for a member of the household of a baroness.","Italian: probably from the feminine form of   Barone  . The name is concentrated in Sondrio province (Lombardy)."]},{"name":"Barren","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Baron   or   Barran  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Baron was born in 1402, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She married Walter of Horewood Pollard esq about 1435, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1402–":"1402–Surnud","1417–Male":"1417–Surnud","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1437–Male":"1437–Surnud","1438–Female":"1438–Surnud","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1445–Male":"1445–Surnud","1402–Female":"1402–Surnud","1437":"1437","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","about 1435":"umbes 1435","1440":"1440","ABT 1437":"umbes 1437","about 1440":"umbes 1440","Abt 1438":"1438","1417":"1417","1438":"1438","Waye by Ashburton, Devon, England":"Waye by Ashburton, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Barnshill, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1402–":"1402–Kuollut","1417–Male":"1417–Kuollut","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","1437–Male":"1437–Kuollut","1438–Female":"1438–Kuollut","1440–Male":"1440–Kuollut","1445–Male":"1445–Kuollut","1402–Female":"1402–Kuollut","1437":"1437","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","about 1435":"noin 1435","1440":"1440","ABT 1437":"noin 1437","about 1440":"noin 1440","Abt 1438":"1438","1417":"1417","1438":"1438","Waye by Ashburton, Devon, England":"Waye by Ashburton, Devon, England","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Barnshill, Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1402–":"1402–Décédée","1417–Male":"1417–Décédé","1435–Male":"1435–Décédé","1437–Male":"1437–Décédé","1438–Female":"1438–Décédée"